functions of local operators.

01:44:55.010 --> 01:44:57.450
It's an important part
of the [INAUDIBLE].

01:44:57.450 --> 01:44:59.180
And in the field
theory, typically,

01:44:59.180 --> 01:45:01.690
when we can see the correlation
function of local operators,

01:45:01.690 --> 01:45:04.305
we use something called a
generating function, though.

01:45:08.220 --> 01:45:10.410
I hope you're
familiar with this.

01:45:10.410 --> 01:45:16.530
Say, again, in the
rating function,

01:45:16.530 --> 01:45:18.957
though-- so now let's
consider Euclidean,

01:45:18.957 --> 01:45:20.206
which is a little bit simpler.

01:45:23.857 --> 01:45:26.440
So essentially, it's a Euclidean
creating correlation function

01:45:26.440 --> 01:45:30.593
by adding such a term
to your field theory.

01:45:38.200 --> 01:45:41.350
And if you want to calculate
correlation functions of O,

01:45:41.350 --> 01:45:43.710
then just take
derivative with phi

01:45:43.710 --> 01:45:45.730
and then satisfy equal to 0.

01:45:45.730 --> 01:45:47.620
Then you get the
correlation function of O.

01:45:47.620 --> 01:45:49.161
So I hope you are
familiar with this.

01:45:54.110 --> 01:45:59.710
so here, you should think of
phi and O as just some, really,

01:45:59.710 --> 01:46:02.140
I have a collection of
all possible operators,

01:46:02.140 --> 01:46:03.930
even though I just
write the single one.

01:46:03.930 --> 01:46:07.100
You should think of them as a
collection of all operators.

01:46:07.100 --> 01:46:09.470
You can put anything
here, stress

01:46:09.470 --> 01:46:11.900
tensor, conserved current,
any scalar operator,

01:46:11.900 --> 01:46:12.650
any spin operator.

01:46:12.650 --> 01:46:14.024
Yeah, you can put
